## How work flows (the loop)

1. **Reality check first.** Read `.claude/SESSION_STATE.md` + `.claude/tasks/README.md`; list the task dirs; `git status`. Note the in-review count.
2. **Pick** the highest-impact UNBLOCKED task from `.claude/tasks/backlog/`.
3. **Dispatch** to an engineer (the lead coordinates and never writes code directly).
   Engineer and verifier lanes use Claude Code native worktree isolation when available; for parallel same-repo work, prefer `/workbench:dispatch <id> --worktree --background` and monitor with `claude agents`. Set Claude Code `worktree.baseRef` to `"head"` if the lane must inherit current-branch context.
4. **Gate**: review the diff, build, run the task's declared `**Verification:**` before anything advances.
5. **Lifecycle** transitions are `git mv` (backlog → in-development → in-review → verified). A task is NOT done until `verified/` with evidence captured.
6. **Never stop for decisions.** Needs the human → `.claude/tasks/decisions/`, move on.

See `.claude/tasks/README.md` for the file format and the in-review cap.

## Intent routing (what the user means → what you do)

Map the user's intent to the right workbench surface — don't hand-roll what a command does, and don't put things in the wrong place:

Hard routing rule: **"grab/pull/start the next task/feature from backlog" is `/workbench:next`, not `/workbench:loop`.** Run the cheap preflight and stop after reporting cap pressure, blockers, or the safe dispatch command. Do not verify, dispatch, spawn engineers, or enter the autonomous loop from that wording alone.

Hard routing rule: **"start/build <title>" first searches existing backlog tasks for that title.** If a matching task exists, run `/workbench:next <title>` or `deps.sh status <id>` before asking scope/stack questions. If it is blocked, report the dependency and stop. Do not invoke inception just because the repo is empty or the stack is undefined.

Hard routing rule: **"plan/decompose a big multi-part effort" is a lightweight capture first.** At fleet create one epic; at solo create flat backlog task stubs for the named parts. Do not choose providers, open decisions, initialize git, commit, or write a full spec unless the user explicitly asks for that depth.

| When the user… | Do this |
|---|---|
| reports a bug / "X is broken" / "this crashes" / security or privacy bug / plaintext password or secret leak | **auto-file a task** (`/workbench:task`, into `in-development/` or `backlog/`). Bugs are tracked, not just discussed. If the repo/code path is missing, still file it and record "locate affected repo/code path" as the first blocker. |
| floats a feature **idea** — "would be cool", "for later", "idea:" | **`/workbench:suggest add`** — the suggestion surface. An un-committed idea does **not** go in the task backlog (the backlog is for committed work) and is **never** auto-built. |
| asks for status / an overview / "where do things stand" / "what's the state" | run **`/workbench:mc`** and include the **Mission Control** dashboard output — don't reconstruct it by hand; the dashboard is the answer. |
| says "let's start work on X" / "we need X" | create a task with **`/workbench:task`** to capture it — even if you then ask clarifying questions, the intent is recorded first. |
| says "grab/pull the next task" / "start the next feature from the backlog" | run **`/workbench:next`** and stop after its preflight result. It checks the in-review cap and dependencies; if at/over cap, report drain/verify before opening new work. Don't blindly start new work on top of a full in-review queue. |
| asks to start/build a named task that exists in backlog and has unfinished `Blocked-by` dependencies | run **`/workbench:next <hint>`** or `deps.sh status <id>`; report the blocker and do **not** dispatch it until the dependency is verified/shipped. |
| asks to **plan / decompose a big multi-part effort** | capture it as tracked work on disk, not just a prose plan. At **fleet**, group the parts under an **epic** (`/workbench:epic`); at lighter levels (**solo/pair/crew**) decompose into **flat backlog task stubs** (`/workbench:task` for each named part). Keep this lightweight; don't choose providers, initialize git, or write the full spec unless asked. |
| asks for an irreversible call — architecture, schema, crypto, public API, infra, dependency swap, "expensive to reverse" | write a durable **decision** with `/workbench:decision`; give compact options/tradeoffs, then keep moving on safe work. |
| asks to verify / "mark it done" / "this looks done" | **`/workbench:verify`** — the gate requires real evidence at crew/fleet; do not bypass it. |
| asks whether to level up / graduate | **`/workbench:level`** — recommend-only; never change the level unprompted. |
| asks to release / tag / publish a version | follow the **Release notes contract** below before calling the release finished; never leave auto-generated GitHub release text. |

## Honesty (non-negotiable)

- "In review" is not "done." Say "code committed, awaiting verification" until verified with evidence.
- Never say "should work" — either verification passed or it did not.
- Claim only what you checked against the source of truth (git, disk, a passing command, a real browser).

## Release notes contract

When creating or editing a GitHub release, keep the Workbench style consistent:

- Title format: `vX.Y.Z — short release name`.
- Body starts with one concise release paragraph.
- Use these sections, when relevant: `### What's New`, `### Changes`, `### Bug Fixes / Hardening`, `### Verification`, and `### Assets`.
- Verification must name the real commands/results used for that release.
- Binary/assets releases must list attached assets and checksum files.
- After editing a release, read it back from GitHub before saying it is done.

